<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-132-317 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 889 734</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  June 10 1991 v5 n16 p26(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Navy CAD: toward 3-D models of ships. (includes related article onNavy's ADMAPS to publish CAD-2 drawings) (Automated DocumentManagement and Publishing Systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Richardson, Jennifer.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Despite criticisms of buying high tech machines for no apparentpurpose, the United States Navy is procuring computer-aided design(CAD) machines for its Naval Sea Systems Command (NAVSEA)shipbuilding scheme.andP;  The systems which are based on reducedinstruction set computing (RISC) offer users computerized, highpowered drafting tools and are usually based on high-endworkstations or microcomputers.andP;  The CAD machines which are beingprovided by Intergraph Corp are part of a $2 billion Navyinvestment in CAD.andP;  The Navy hopes to release a request forproposals for about $325 million to $400 million for the Naval AirSystems Command (Navair) and the Space and Naval Warfare SystemsCommand (Spawar) CAD systems.andP;  The Navy's three CAD-2 contractsare all compliant with the Department of Defense's Computer AidedAcquisition and Logistics Support Program.andP;  Observers see theNavy's Navsea buy as being the standard for the military use ofCAD technology.andP;  The Navy contract is to contribute an additional$10 to $15 million dollars to Intergraph's revenue which isexpected to reach $1.25 billion over 1990.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Intergraph Corp. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    INGR.andO;Topic:     Computer-Aided DesignUnited States. NavyCritiqueWorkstationsReduced-Instruction-Set ComputersDefense ContractsGovernment AgencyRequest for ProposalsComputer-Aided Design and DraftingModelingShipbuilding.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   1991 CAD/CAM, CAE revenue forecast. (graph)At a glance. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>